const worldStories: Story[] = [
  { id: "s83", topic: "world", title: "The village that *banned smartphones* — and got happier", summary: "A 500-person Irish village voted to prohibit smartphones for anyone under 18. Mental health referrals dropped 40%.", body: `Greystones, a coastal village of 500 people in County Wicklow, Ireland, held a public vote in September 2025: should smartphones be prohibited for residents under 18? The measure passed with 71% support.\n\nThe ban is technically voluntary — a social compact rather than a law. But compliance has been near-total. Parents in the community surrendered their children's smartphones and replaced them with basic phones capable of calls and texts.\n\nSix months later, the village GP reports a 40% decline in mental health referrals for adolescents. Teachers report improved concentration and a measurable increase in homework quality. The local GAA club says youth attendance at training has doubled.\n\n"We're not Luddites," says one parent who organized the vote. "We're just asking: what if the phone isn't helping? The data from our village says it wasn't."`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 16 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m83" },
  { id: "s84", topic: "world", title: "The country that just *elected a 31-year-old* prime minister", summary: "Finland already did it. Now Chile has the youngest head of government in the Americas. His first policy: universal basic income.", body: `Matías Ibáñez was inaugurated as Chile's youngest-ever president last month at 31. His first executive action: a universal basic income pilot for the Atacama region, funded by lithium export revenues.\n\nThe policy mirrors proposals that have been tested in Finland, Kenya, and several U.S. cities, but with a distinctive twist: the payment amount is indexed to local cost of living rather than a flat national rate. Residents of mining towns will receive more than residents of Santiago.\n\nIbáñez's election was driven by voters under 35, who turned out at historically unprecedented rates. His campaign was notable for what it didn't promise: no sweeping nationalizations, no confrontation with mining companies, no revolutionary rhetoric. "Boring radicalism," one journalist called it.\n\nThe opposition is cautious rather than hostile. "Let him try," said one conservative senator. "If it works, we'll all claim we supported it."`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 28 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m84" },
  { id: "s85", topic: "world", title: "The *floating city* that just got its first permanent residents", summary: "A 300-person community on modular platforms off the coast of Busan, South Korea, is now officially inhabited.", body: `OCEANIX Busan, the world's first floating city prototype, welcomed its first 50 permanent residents in March. The community occupies three interconnected platforms totaling 6.3 hectares, anchored two kilometers off the coast of Busan, South Korea.\n\nEach platform is designed to be self-sustaining: solar panels and wave energy generators provide power, desalination units produce fresh water, and vertical farms grow a portion of residents' food. Waste is processed on-site.\n\nThe residents — selected from 12,000 applicants — are a mix of researchers, entrepreneurs, and families. Monthly costs are comparable to living in central Busan, subsidized by the project's consortium of backers including UN-Habitat and Samsung.\n\nThe experiment is designed to test whether floating communities can serve as a scalable response to sea-level rise. If the Busan prototype succeeds, larger versions are planned for Bangladesh, the Maldives, and the Marshall Islands.`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 36 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m85" },
  { id: "s86", topic: "world", title: "The *passport* that three countries now accept as valid — but no nation issued", summary: "A digital identity project is creating a stateless passport recognized by Estonia, Singapore, and Paraguay. The UN is watching closely.", body: `The Bitnation World Citizenship passport is not issued by any sovereign nation. It exists as a cryptographic credential on a blockchain, verified by a decentralized network of identity validators. As of this month, three countries — Estonia, Singapore, and Paraguay — accept it as a valid form of identification for certain purposes.\n\nThe acceptance is limited: it works for opening bank accounts and registering businesses, not for visa-free entry. But the symbolism is significant. For the first time, a non-state identity document has been recognized by multiple sovereign governments.\n\nThe project's founder argues that identity should not depend on birth location. "Two billion people worldwide lack recognized identification," she says. "Many of them are stateless, refugees, or victims of administrative failure. We're building an alternative."\n\nCritics worry about accountability: if no state issues the passport, no state is responsible for its misuse.`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 49 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m86" },
  { id: "s87", topic: "world", title: "The African Union just launched *its own GPS system*", summary: "AfriGNSS will provide meter-accurate positioning across the continent. The geopolitical implications are significant.", body: `The African Union officially launched AfriGNSS — the African Global Navigation Satellite System — with the deployment of four initial satellites into medium Earth orbit. When complete, the 24-satellite constellation will provide meter-accurate positioning across the entire African continent.\n\nThe project, funded primarily by the AU's member states with technical support from India and Japan, is designed to reduce the continent's dependence on GPS (American), GLONASS (Russian), Galileo (European), and BeiDou (Chinese).\n\n"Positioning data is sovereignty data," said the project's director. "When your farmers, your military, and your aviation system depend on another nation's satellites, you are dependent in ways that aren't obvious until those satellites are turned off."\n\nThe system will also provide higher accuracy than existing GNSS services in sub-Saharan Africa, where signal availability has historically been worse than in northern latitudes.`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 62 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m87" },
  { id: "s88", topic: "world", title: "The *underground city* that keeps growing beneath Helsinki", summary: "Finland's capital has 10 million square meters of usable space under its streets. Swimming pools, data centers, and a church.", body: `Beneath Helsinki's streets lies a parallel city. Over the past four decades, the Finnish capital has excavated approximately 10 million square meters of underground space — enough to accommodate the entire above-ground footprint of the city center.\n\nThe underground city includes swimming pools, shopping centers, a hockey rink, a church, parking for 10,000 cars, data centers, and an emergency shelter system capable of housing 900,000 people — more than the city's entire population.\n\nThe original motivation was military: during the Cold War, Finland maintained a policy of civil defense preparedness that required extensive underground shelter capacity. The spaces have since been converted to civilian use, creating a second city that operates year-round regardless of weather.\n\n"In a country where winter lasts six months, putting things underground is just common sense," says Helsinki's chief architect. "The question is why more northern cities haven't done the same."`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 71 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m88" },
  { id: "s89", topic: "world", title: "The *refugee camp* that became a city of 400,000 — and wants independence", summary: "Dadaab in Kenya has existed for 32 years. It has hospitals, markets, and a university. Its residents are demanding political recognition.", body: `Dadaab refugee camp in northeastern Kenya was established in 1991 as a temporary settlement for Somalis fleeing civil war. Thirty-two years later, it is home to approximately 400,000 people and has all the infrastructure of a mid-sized city: hospitals, schools, markets, a bus system, and a satellite campus of a Nairobi university.\n\nResidents of Dadaab have begun organizing for political recognition — not as refugees, but as a self-governing community. A council of elected leaders has drafted a charter requesting "autonomous zone" status within Kenya, similar to what some indigenous communities hold in other countries.\n\nThe Kenyan government has not responded officially. The UNHCR has expressed concern that political recognition could set a precedent that discourages host countries from accepting refugees.\n\n"We have been 'temporary' for thirty-two years," said the council's chairperson. "At some point, temporary becomes permanent. We deserve to be governed by people we choose, not managed by agencies we didn't invite."`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 79 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m89" },
  { id: "s90", topic: "world", title: "The bridge connecting two countries that *neither government approved*", summary: "Residents of a border village in Laos and Vietnam built a footbridge with their own money. Customs officials are baffled.", body: `The bridge is 40 meters long, made of steel cable and wooden planks, and spans a narrow stretch of the Mekong River between the village of Pak Beng in Laos and Mường Xén in Vietnam. It was built in three weeks by residents of both villages, funded entirely by private contributions totaling approximately $12,000.\n\nNeither the Lao nor Vietnamese government authorized its construction. There is no customs post, no immigration checkpoint, and no legal framework for cross-border pedestrian traffic at this location.\n\nThe villagers' reasoning is pragmatic: families on both sides of the river are intermarried. The nearest official border crossing is 80 kilometers away. A bridge that takes three minutes to walk was more practical than a four-hour drive.\n\nBorder officials have inspected the bridge and found it structurally sound. The legal question — what to do about an unauthorized international crossing that nobody wants to close — remains unresolved.`, publishedAt: new Date(REF - 86 * 60 * 60 * 1000).toISOString(), marketId: "m90" },
];

